1 Interpreting Least Squares Parameters (6 points)

Suppose we have a data set with five predictors,

  • \(X1 =\) GPA,
  • \(X2 =\) IQ,
  • \(X3 =\) Gender (1 for Female and 0 for Male),
  • \(X4 =\) Interaction between GPA and IQ, and
  • \(X5 =\) Interaction between GPA and Gender.

The response variable is starting salary after graduation (in thousands of dollars).

Assume we use least squares to fit a model, and get

  • \(\beta_0 = 60\),
  • \(\beta_1 = 20\),
  • \(\beta_2 = 0.07\),
  • \(\beta_3 = 15\),
  • \(\beta_4 = 0.01\),
  • \(\beta_5 = -5\).
  1. Which of the following statements is most correct and why?

  1. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, males earn more on average than females.

  2. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, females earn more on average than males.

  3. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, males earn more on average than females if the GPA is high enough.

  4. For a fixed value of IQ and GPA, females earn more on average than males if the GPA is high enough.

  1. Answer (iii) is correct.

The equation of fitted model is: \[\text{Predicted starting salary} = 60 + 20\, \text{GPA} + 0.07\,\text{IQ} + 15\,\text{Gender} + 0.01\,\text{GPA}*\text{IQ} â 5\,\text{GPA}*\text{Gender}\]

For females (Gender = 1): \[\begin{align} \text{Predicted starting salary} &= 60 +20\,\text{GPA} + 0.07\,\text{IQ} + 15 + 0.01\,\text{GPA}*\text{IQ} -5\,\text{GPA} \\ &= (60 + 15) + (20-5)\text{GPA} + 0.07\,\text{IQ} + 0.01\,\text{GPA}*\text{IQ} \\ &= 75 + 15\,\text{GPA} + 0.07\,\text{IQ} + 0.01\,\text{GPA}*\text{IQ} \end{align}\]

For males (Gender = 0): \[\text{Predicted starting salary} = 60 + 20\,\text{GPA} + 0.07\,\text{IQ} + 0 + 0.01\,\text{GPA}*\text{IQ} +0\]

Given the same GPA and IQ, the difference between the predicted salaries for a female and for a male is \[\begin{align} \Delta_{F-M}(\text{Salary})&= (75 + 15\,\text{GPA} + 0.07\,\text{IQ} + 0.01\,\text{GPA}*\text{IQ}) \\ & \quad - (60 + 20\,\text{GPA} + 0.07\,\text{IQ} + 0.01\,\text{GPA}*\text{IQ})\\ &= 15 - 5\,\text{GPA}. \end{align}\]

  • Hence for equal GPAs and IQs, a female is expected to earn more (the \(\delta\) is positive) if the GPA satisfies \(15 - 5\,\text{GPA}>0\) which is the same as \(5*\text{GPA} â 15 < 0\), i.e., if \(\text{GPA} < 3.0\).
  • If the common GPAs is less than 3.0, a female is expected to earn more, and if both of them have the same GPA = 3.0, their predicted salaries are the same.
  1. Predict the salary of a female with IQ of 110 and a GPA of 4.0.

Predicted starting salary = \(75 + 15\,\text{GPA} + 0.07\,\text{IQ} + 0.01\,\text{GPA}*\text{IQ}\)

Predicted starting salary = \(75 + 15*4 + 0.07*110 + 0.01*4*110\)

For a female with \(IQ=110\) and \(GPA=4.0\), the predicted starting salary is $147,100.

r 75 + 15*4 + 0.07*110 + 0.01*4*110

  1. True or False: Since the coefficient for the GPA/IQ interaction term is very small, there is very little evidence of an interaction effect. Justify your answer.

False. The interaction may be either significant or not, but the stated reasoning is wrong. We can only judge how small the coefficient is by testing it. The \(t\)-statistic of this test will standardize the coefficient, dividing it by its standard error (estimated standard deviation of the estimated slope).

Depending on this standard error, the coefficient of 0.01 may appear significant. A significant coefficient will result in a low \(p\)-value from a \(t\) distribution with the appropriate degrees of freedom.

  1. 627 Only. Use the formula for a regression line \(y=\hat{\beta}_0+ \hat{\beta}_1 x\) to show, in the case of simple linear regression, the least squares line always passes through the point of the averages \((\bar{x},\bar{y})\).

To verify if a given point belongs to a given line, plug in the coordinates \(x=\bar{x}\) and \(y=\bar{y}\) into the equation of the line \(y=\hat{\beta}_0+ \hat{\beta}_1x\), where \(\hat{\beta}_1=\frac{\sum(x-\bar{x})(y_i-\bar{y})}{\sum(x_i-\bar{x})^2}\) and \(\hat{\beta}_0=\bar{y} -\hat{\beta}_1 \bar{x}\)

We get: \(\bar{y}=(\bar{y} - \beta_1\bar{x})+\hat{\beta}_1\bar{x}=\bar{y}\) We obtained a true identity, therefore, the point \((\bar{x},\bar{y})\) is on the simple regression line.

2 Training and Test Residual Sums of Squares (4 Points)

I collect a set of data (\(n = 100\) observations) containing a single predictor and a quantitative response. I then fit a linear regression model to the data, to include a separate cubic regression, i.e.,

\[Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1X + \beta_2X^2 + \beta_3X^3 + \epsilon\]

  1. Suppose the true relationship between \(X\) and \(Y\) is linear, i.e., \(Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1X\). Consider the training residual sum of squares (RSS) for the linear regression, and also the training RSS for the cubic regression. Would we expect one to be lower than the other, would we expect them to be the same, or is there not enough information to tell? Justify your answer.

  2. Answer (a) using test rather than training RSS.

  3. Suppose the true relationship between \(X\) and \(Y\) is not linear, but we donât know how far it is from linear. Consider the training RSS for the linear regression, and also the training RSS for the cubic regression. Would we expect one to be lower than the other, would we expect them to be the same, or is there not enough information to tell? Justify your answer.

  4. Answer (c) using test rather than training RSS.

  1. Adding new variables can only reduce the training SSerr, so we expect the training SSerr from the cubic regression model to be smaller.

Since a cubic regression is more flexible, it will fit the given 100 points closer, with smaller residuals, and this will result in a smaller residual sum of squares.

Technically, they can be the same as well, if residuals from the linear model appear perfectly uncorrelated with the additional predictors \(X^2\)and \(X^3\) (but that would be quite a coincidence).

  1. Since the true relationship is linear, the cubic model is expected to provide a larger test SSerr. Using a less flexible linear model results in a lower variance. Also, the linear model is correct, so there is no bias. Therefore, the linear model has a smaller test MSE, and therefore, we expect a smaller test SSerr.

  2. Regardless of the true model, the additional terms \(X^2\)and \(X^3\) will explain some additional portion of the total sum of squares SStot, and therefore, will reduce SSerr.

  3. Although estimates from a linear model will have a lower variance, they will be biased, because the linear model is incorrect.

In this case, we cannot tell, from the given information, which model produces a smaller test SSerr. It depends on the balance of the variance and the squared bias.

The 95% confidence intervals mean that out of 100 independent trials that each use the same method to calculate the test statistic, the true value of the parameter will be within the confidence interval for at least 95 of the trials, we just donât know which trials.
